To search the entire classpath for a specific annotation in Java, you can use reflection and the ClassLoader to find and examine all the classes loaded. Here is some sample code you can use:

```java
public static List<Class<?>> findAnnotatedClasses(Class<? extends Annotation> annotation, String packageName) throws IOException, ClassNotFoundException {
    List<Class<?>> classes = new ArrayList<>();
    ClassLoader classLoader = Thread.currentThread().getContextClassLoader();
    String path = packageName.replace('.', '/');
    Enumeration<URL> resources = classLoader.getResources(path);

    while (resources.hasMoreElements()) {
        URL resource = resources.nextElement();
        File file = new File(resource.getFile());
        if (file.isDirectory()) {
            String[] fileList = file.list();
            for (String f : fileList) {
                String fileName = f.endsWith(".class") ? f.substring(0, f.length() - 6) : f;
                Class<?> clazz = Class.forName(packageName + "." + fileName);
                if (clazz.isAnnotationPresent(annotation)) {
                    classes.add(clazz);
                }
            }
        } else {
            // Handle jar files
            try (JarInputStream jar = new JarInputStream(resource.openStream())) {
                JarEntry entry;
                while ((entry = jar.getNextJarEntry()) != null) {
                    if (entry.getName().endsWith(".class")) {
                        String className = entry.getName().substring(0, entry.getName().length() - 6).replace('/', '.');
                        Class<?> clazz = Class.forName(className);
                        if (clazz.isAnnotationPresent(annotation)) {
                            classes.add(clazz);
                        }
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }

    return classes;
}
```

Here's an example of how to use it:

```java
List<Class<?>> annotatedClasses = findAnnotatedClasses(MyAnnotation.class, "com.example");
```

This code will search the package "com.example" for all classes annotated with "MyAnnotation". If you want to search the entire classpath, pass an empty string as the package name.

Keep in mind that scanning the entire classpath can be slow and should be done sparingly, especially in production environments. In general, it's better to use a more targeted approach if possible.

