An alternate solution is to use implicit parameters with a type class. This approach allows you to define a set of methods that can take arguments of different types, without the need for overloading. 

Here is an example of how this might work:

```
trait MyTypeClass[T] {
  def method(arg: T): String
}

object MyTypeClass {
  implicit object intInstance extends MyTypeClass[Int] {
    def method(arg: Int): String = s"You passed an Int: $arg"
  }

  implicit object stringInstance extends MyTypeClass[String] {
    def method(arg: String): String = s"You passed a String: $arg"
  }
}

def myMethod[T](arg: T)(implicit ev: MyTypeClass[T]): String = {
  ev.method(arg)
}
```

In this example, we define a type class `MyTypeClass` that has a single method `method` which takes an argument of type `T` and returns a `String`. We then define instances of this type class for both `Int` and `String`, which implement the `method` method appropriately. Finally, we define a generic method `myMethod` which takes a single argument of type `T` and an implicit parameter of type `MyTypeClass[T]`. Within this method, we call the `method` method on the implicit instance of `MyTypeClass` for the type of `arg`.

To use this method, you simply call `myMethod` with an argument of any type for which you have defined an instance of `MyTypeClass`. The appropriate implementation of the `method` method will be chosen automatically based on the type of the argument.

This approach allows you to define a set of methods for all the different types you want to support, without the need for overloading. It also allows you to add support for new types in a modular way, by simply defining a new instance of `MyTypeClass` for the new type.

Regarding your question about implicit conversions, Scala does have built-in implicit conversions, which can be defined using the `implicit` keyword. However, it is generally not a good idea to define these conversions in the standard library or to rely on them heavily in your code, as they can lead to unexpected behavior and make your code harder to understand and maintain. Instead, it is better to use implicit parameters and type classes to define conversions and other types of behavior that you want to be implicit. 

