  // move to the previous input if left arrow key is pressed
  if (event.key === 'ArrowLeft') {
    const currentIndex = Array.from(inputs).indexOf(focused);
    if (currentIndex !== 0) {
      const prevInput = inputs[currentIndex - 1];
      prevInput.focus();
    }
  }
});
```

In this example, we first get all input elements in the table using `querySelectorAll()`. We then add a `keydown` event listener to the document to listen for arrow key presses. When the arrow keys are pressed, we get the currently focused input element using `document.activeElement`. We then calculate the index of the focused input in the `inputs` array using `Array.from(inputs).indexOf(focused)`. Finally, we use the `focus()` method to move the focus to the next/previous input element in the `inputs` array. Note that we check if the current index is not the first or last input element, respectively, to prevent moving the focus beyond the bounds of the input elements array.

