To enable range-based for loops to work with user-defined types, you need to provide a way for the compiler to know how to iterate over your custom container. The easiest way to do this is to define the member functions `begin()` and `end()` for your type.

For example, let's say you have a custom container called `MyContainer` that stores integers. You can define `begin()` and `end()` functions for it like this:

```c++
class MyContainer {
public:
    // Constructor and other member functions here

    int* begin() { return &myData[0]; }
    int* end() { return &myData[size]; }

private:
    int myData[10];
    int size = 10;
};
```

Now you can use range-based for loops with your custom container:

```c++
MyContainer myContainer;

for (int& x : myContainer) {
    std::cout << x << std::endl;
}
```

If your custom container belongs to a namespace, you should define `begin()` and `end()` within that namespace. For example:

```c++
namespace MyNamespace {
    class MyContainer {
    public:
        // Constructor and other member functions here

        int* begin() { return &myData[0]; }
        int* end() { return &myData[size]; }

    private:
        int myData[10];
        int size = 10;
    };
}
```

Finally, if your custom container already provides iterators, you can define `begin()` and `end()` to return those iterators. For example:

```c++
class MyContainer {
public:
    // Constructor and other member functions here

    std::vector<int>::iterator begin() { return myData.begin(); }
    std::vector<int>::iterator end() { return myData.end(); }

private:
    std::vector<int> myData;
};
```

Overall, the guidelines for defining `begin()` and `end()` for your user-defined types are to provide functions that return iterators that represent the beginning and end of the range you want to iterate over. If you have any doubts, you can refer to the C++11 specification or consult blogs and documentation on the topic.

