string hex = Convert.ToString(number, 16); // convert to hexadecimal base (base 16)
```

This will convert the number 12345 to binary and hexadecimal formats respectively. However, this only works for bases 2, 8, 10, and 16.

To convert to a custom base, you can use the following code:

```
public static string ConvertToBase(int number, string baseChars)
{
    if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(baseChars))
        throw new ArgumentException("There must be at least one character to represent the base", nameof(baseChars));

    int baseNumber = baseChars.Length;
    if (baseNumber == 1)
        throw new ArgumentException("There must be at least two characters to represent a base", nameof(baseChars));

    bool isNegative = number < 0;
    number = Math.Abs(number);
    StringBuilder result = new StringBuilder();

    while (number > 0)
    {
        result.Insert(0, baseChars[number % baseNumber]);
        number /= baseNumber;
    }

    if (isNegative)
        result.Insert(0, '-');

    return result.ToString();
}
```

You can call this method with the number and a string of all the characters you want to use in the base. For example:

```
int number = 12345;
string baseChars = "0123456789abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyzABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ";
string customBase = ConvertToBase(number, baseChars);
```

This will convert the number to a base with the characters specified in `baseChars`.

Note that this implementation uses a `StringBuilder` rather than concatenating strings, which should give better performance.

