PreparedStatements in Java are a feature of JDBC (Java Database Connectivity) that allow for parameterized queries. When using PreparedStatements, you construct a SQL query with placeholders for parameters, which are later filled in with actual values at runtime. This is done using the set methods provided by the PreparedStatement object.

The key advantage of using PreparedStatement over constructing SQL using concatenation (string building) is that a PreparedStatement is precompiled, that means it is compiled once on creation and hence speedup database execution time faster than SQL queries constructed using regular string concatenation. Also, parameter values are treated as data not as part of the SQL statement so no SQL interpretation is possible by hacker.

For instance, the following code is an example of how to use a PreparedStatement:

```
String query = "SELECT * FROM users WHERE name = ?";
PreparedStatement pstmt = conn.prepareStatement(query);
pstmt.setString(1, "John Doe");
ResultSet rs = pstmt.executeQuery();
```

In this example, the `?` serves as a placeholder for the parameter value, which is set using the `setString()` method. The SQL query that is executed against the database contains the placeholder for the parameter value, not the actual value itself.

Overall, using PreparedStatements is a recommended best practice to avoid/prevent SQL injection attacks in Java applications.

