This syntax tells React to use the previous state value to calculate the new state value, rather than just replacing it. You can then make the changes you want on the previous state, before returning the updated value.

Secondly, to improve performance and avoid unnecessary re-renders when the content of an object or array hasn't changed, you can use the `useMemo` hook. This hook will memoize the value returned from a function, and only recalculate it when its dependencies change.

For example, if you have a complicated calculation that generates a new object or array, you can memoize it by defining it as a function and passing it as the first argument to `useMemo`, and then passing an array of its dependencies as the second argument. Here's an example:

