No, it is not valid HTML to nest a `<form>` element within another `<form>` element. According to the HTML5 specification, "A form element cannot be a descendant of the `<form>` element that it creates." This means that any form elements contained within the inner form will not be submitted when the outer form is submitted, regardless of whether the submit button pressed belonged to "a" or "b".

A simple workaround for this would be to place the form elements from both "a" and "b" within one single form, and use JavaScript to manipulate which fields are submitted based on which submit button is pressed.

Here's an example of how this could work:

```
<form id="myForm">
  <!--Fields for section "a"-->
  <input type="text" name="field1">
  <input type="text" name="field2">

  <!--Fields for section "b"-->
  <div id="bFields">
    <input type="text" name="field3">
    <input type="text" name="field4">
  </div>

  <!--Submit buttons-->
  <button type="submit" name="submitButton" value="a">Submit A</button>
  <button type="submit" name="submitButton" value="b">Submit B</button>
</form>

<script>
  const myForm = document.getElementById("myForm");
  const bFields = document.getElementById("bFields");

  // Listen for form submit event
  myForm.addEventListener("submit", function(event) {
    // Prevent default form submission
    event.preventDefault();

    // Get the active submit button value
    const submitButtonValue = event.submitter.value;

    // Check if the "b" submit button was clicked
    if (submitButtonValue === "b") {
      // Remove the "b" fields from the submitted data
      bFields.remove();
    }

    // Submit the form with modified data
    myForm.submit();
  });
</script>
```

This JavaScript code listens for the form submission event and modifies the form data before submitting it based on which submit button was clicked. If the "b" button is clicked, the fields in the `bFields` div are removed from the form before submission. Otherwise, all fields are submitted as usual.

