    const ushort IMAGE_FILE_MACHINE_I386 = 0x014c;

    bool isX86 = (header.Machine == IMAGE_FILE_MACHINE_I386);
    ```

You can put these steps in a method that takes an assembly file path and returns a boolean indicating whether it was built for x86. Keep in mind that if the assembly was built for Any CPU, it will run as x86 on 32-bit systems and x64 on 64-bit systems. So, if you need to check if an assembly will run on a 64-bit system, you need to use a different approach. One common method is to try loading the assembly in a separate 64-bit process and catching any exceptions that occur.

To perform an asynchronous directory search using `fs.readdir`, you can use recursion along with Promises. Here's an example function that returns a Promise which resolves to an array of all files in the given directory and its subdirectories:

```
const fs = require('fs');
const path = require('path');

function getAllFiles(dirPath) {
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    fs.readdir(dirPath, { withFileTypes: true }, async (err, files) => {
      if (err) {
        return reject(err);
      }

      const filesArray = [];

      for (const file of files) {
        const filePath = path.join(dirPath, file.name);
        if (file.isDirectory()) {
          const subFiles = await getAllFiles(filePath);
          filesArray.push(...subFiles);
        } else {
          filesArray.push(filePath);
        }
      }

      resolve(filesArray);
    });
  });
}
```

To use this function, simply call it with the path to the directory you want to search, like this:

```
getAllFiles('/path/to/directory')
  .then(files => {
    console.log(files);
  })
  .catch(err => {
    console.error(err);
  });
```

This function uses `fs.readdir` with the `withFileTypes` option to get information about each file and directory in the given directory. It then uses recursion to call itself with each subdirectory it finds, and adds the resulting files to an array. Finally, it resolves the Promise with the resulting array.

