When authenticating with client certificates in Java, the client must present a certificate chain to the server. The certificate chain should include the client's own certificate, as well as all intermediate certificates leading up to the root CA certificate that signed the client's certificate. Additionally, the private key associated with the client's certificate should also be included. 

The client's certificate and private key should be stored in a keystore file. A keystore is a protected database that holds a private key and one or more corresponding certificates. The keystore file should be in a format that is compatible with Java, such as JKS or PKCS12.

To set up your Java client to use client certificates for authentication, you can use the Java Secure Socket Extension (JSSE) API. Here is some sample code that shows how to set up a SSLContext object with client authentication enabled:

```
// Load keystore file
KeyStore keystore = KeyStore.getInstance("JKS");
keystore.load(new FileInputStream("keystore.jks"), "password".toCharArray());

// Set up trust manager
TrustManagerFactory tmf = TrustManagerFactory.getInstance(TrustManagerFactory.getDefaultAlgorithm());
tmf.init(keystore);

// Set up key manager
KeyManagerFactory kmf = KeyManagerFactory.getInstance(KeyManagerFactory.getDefaultAlgorithm());
kmf.init(keystore, "password".toCharArray());

// Set up SSL context
SSLContext sslContext = SSLContext.getInstance("TLS");
sslContext.init(kmf.getKeyManagers(), tmf.getTrustManagers(), null);

// Open SSL connection using the SSL context
SSLSocketFactory sslSocketFactory = sslContext.getSocketFactory();
SSLSocket sslSocket = (SSLSocket) sslSocketFactory.createSocket("example.com", 443);
sslSocket.startHandshake();
```

