Yes, it's true that semaphores were removed from the C++11 standard and will not be included in C++17 either. However, there are still alternatives available, such as condition variables. 

In a nutshell, condition variables allow one or more threads to wait for a signal from another thread indicating that a certain condition has been met. Here's a simple example that demonstrates how a condition variable can be used to achieve the same functionality as a semaphore:

```c++
#include <iostream>
#include <thread>
#include <mutex>
#include <condition_variable>

std::mutex mtx;
std::condition_variable cv;
bool ready = false;

void thread_function(int id)
{
    std::unique_lock<std::mutex> lock(mtx);

    while(!ready)
    {
        std::cout << "Thread " << id << " is waiting" << std::endl;
        cv.wait(lock); // wait for signal from main thread
    }

    std::cout << "Thread " << id << " is done" << std::endl;
}

int main()
{
    std::thread threads[2];

    for(int i = 0; i < 2; ++i)
    {
        threads[i] = std::thread(thread_function, i);
    }

    std::cout << "Main thread is sleeping..." << std::endl;
    std::this_thread::sleep_for(std::chrono::seconds(3));

    {
        std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(mtx);
        ready = true;
        std::cout << "Sending signal to threads..." << std::endl;
    }

    cv.notify_all(); // send signal to all waiting threads

    for(auto& th : threads)
    {
        th.join();
    }

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, two threads are created that will wait for a signal from the main thread before proceeding. To achieve this, a mutex and a condition variable are used. The threads enter a loop where they wait for the signal by calling the `wait` method on the condition variable. When the main thread is ready, it sets the `ready` flag to `true`, unlocks the mutex, and sends a signal to all waiting threads using `notify_all`.

