The reason why `List.remove()` is not generic is because it removes the first occurrence of the specified element from the list, and the element can be any type (not just the generic type parameter of the list). 

If `List.remove()` were generic, it would remove only the elements of the type specified in the generic type parameter of the list. This could be useful in certain cases, but it would also limit the flexibility of the method.

However, you can achieve a similar effect by using the `List.removeIf()` method, which was introduced in Java 8. This method takes a `Predicate` that tests each element of the list, and removes all elements that satisfy the predicate. Here's an example:

```
List<String> list = new ArrayList<>();
list.add("foo");
list.add("bar");
list.add("baz");

list.removeIf(s -> s.equals("foo")); // removes "foo" from the list

list.forEach(System.out::println); // prints "bar", "baz"
```

In this example, the lambda expression `s -> s.equals("foo")` is a predicate that tests whether each element of the list is equal to "foo". The `list.removeIf()` method removes all elements that satisfy the predicate, so "foo" is removed from the list.

