When you pass a lambda function directly, the compiler needs to deduce the type of the lambda function itself, and then deduce the type of the function parameter. This can be tricky for the compiler, because the type deduction rules can sometimes be complicated.

One way to provide a hint to the compiler is to use the `decltype` keyword, like in the alternative function you provided. `decltype` allows you to deduce the type of an expression at compile time. So, for example, if you have a set of integers called `my_set`, you could use `decltype(*my_set.begin())` to deduce the type of the elements in the set.

Another way to provide a hint to the compiler is to use the `std::function` wrapper. `std::function` provides a type-erased function object that can store any callable object, including lambda functions. So, for example, you could rewrite your function to take a `std::function` parameter, like this:

```
template<typename T>
std::set<T> filter(const std::set<T>& s, std::function<bool(const T&)> pred) {
