Yes, you can use `Promise.allSettled()` instead of `Promise.all()`. `Promise.allSettled()` waits until all promises in the array have settled (fulfilled or rejected), but does not return the resolved data. Instead, it returns an array of objects, one for each promise, indicating whether the promise was fulfilled or rejected. 

Here's an example: 

```
const promises = [promise1, promise2, promise3, ...];

Promise.allSettled(promises)
  .then(results => {
    // do something with the results
  })
  .catch(error => {
    // handle errors
  });
```

In this example, `promises` is an array of promises, and `Promise.allSettled(promises)` waits until all promises have settled. Once all promises have settled, it returns an array of objects indicating whether each promise was fulfilled or rejected, e.g.:

```
[
  {status: "fulfilled", value: "result of promise1"},
  {status: "rejected", reason: "error message"},
  {status: "fulfilled", value: "result of promise3"},
  ...
]
```

Note that `Promise.allSettled()` is a relatively new addition to the JavaScript language and may not be supported in all browsers or environments. If you're using an older version of JavaScript or need to support older browsers, you can use a polyfill like `promise.allSettled` or equivalent libraries which returns a subset of Promise.allSettled values.

Static methods are not overridable in Java because they are not tied to an instance of a class. Overriding is done when a method in a subclass has the same signature as a method in its superclass, and when a method is overridden, the implementation in the subclass is used instead of the one in the superclass. However, static methods belong to the class rather than an instance of the class, so they cannot be overridden in the same way.

Regarding your design goal of using an interface to enforce a coding convention, it is possible to use a combination of an interface and an abstract class to achieve the desired behavior. In this case, you can define an abstract class that implements the interface and provides a default implementation for the static constructor method, while also defining it as abstract. Then, any subclasses can choose to either implement the method themselves or use the default implementation provided by the abstract class. This combination allows you to enforce the coding convention without relying on just a comment in the interface.

Here is an example of how this can be done:

```
public interface IXMLizable {
   public static Foo newInstanceFromXML(Element e);
}

public abstract class AbstractXMLizable implements IXMLizable {
   public static Foo newInstanceFromXML(Element e) {
      // default implementation
      return new Foo();
   }
}

public class Bar extends AbstractXMLizable {
   // implementation for newInstanceFromXML method
}
```

In this example, `AbstractXMLizable` implements the `IXMLizable` interface and provides a default implementation for the `newInstanceFromXML` method. `Bar` extends `AbstractXMLizable` and can choose to either implement the method itself or use the default implementation from the abstract class.

The ISO-8601 standard defines the first week of a year as the week containing January 4th, with the first day of the week being Monday. This means that if January 1 is on a Friday, Saturday, or Sunday, it is part of the last week of the previous year, and if it is on a Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, or Thursday, it is part of the first week of the current year.

Therefore, in the ISO-8601 standard, 2012-12-31 is considered part of Week 1 of 2013.

If you need to calculate this programmatically, you can use the built-in functions in your programming language or library that support ISO-8601 week numbering. For example, in Python, you can use the `isocalendar()` method of the `datetime` class:

```python
import datetime

date = datetime.date(2012, 12, 31)
year, week_num, day_of_week = date.isocalendar()

print("Year:", year)
print("Week number:", week_num)
print("Day of week:", day_of_week)
```

This would output:

```
Year: 2013
Week number: 1
Day of week: 1
```

If your programming language or library does not have built-in support for ISO-8601 week numbering, you can use external libraries or algorithms that implement this standard. For example, in Java, you can use the `ISOWeek` class from the ThreeTen-Extra library:

```java
import org.threeten.extra.YearWeek;

LocalDate date = LocalDate.of(2012, 12, 31);
YearWeek yearWeek = YearWeek.from(date);

System.out.println("Year: " + yearWeek.getYear());
System.out.println("Week number: " + yearWeek.getWeek());
System.out.println("Day of week: " + date.getDayOfWeek());
```

This would output:

```
Year: 2013
Week number: 1
Day of week: MONDAY
```

Alternatively, you can implement the algorithm yourself using the rules laid out in the ISO-8601 standard. Here is an example implementation in JavaScript:

```javascript
function getIsoWeekNumber(date) {
  const year = date.getFullYear();
  const month = date.getMonth();
  const day = date.getDate();

  const jan4 = new Date(year, 0, 4);
  const jan4DayOfWeek = (jan4.getDay() + 6) % 7;  // Adjust day of week to start from Monday (0)

  const daysSinceJan4 = (dayOfYear(date) - dayOfYear(jan4)) + jan4DayOfWeek;
  const weekNumber = Math.floor(daysSinceJan4 / 7) + 1;

  if (weekNumber === 53 && daysSinceJan4 < 365) {
    return 1;  // Week 53 only occurs if it includes January 4th of the next year
  }

  return weekNumber;
}

function dayOfYear(date) {
  const startOfYear = new Date(date.getFullYear(), 0, 0);
  const diff = date.getTime() - startOfYear.getTime();
  const oneDay = 1000 * 60 * 60 * 24;
  return Math.floor(diff / oneDay);
}

const date = new Date(2012, 11, 31);

console.log("Year:", date.getFullYear());
console.log("Week number:", getIsoWeekNumber(date));
console.log("Day of week:", date.getDay());
```

This would output:

```
Year: 2012
Week number: 1
Day of week: 1
```

