To achieve the desired output of a nested array based on parent-child relationships in a flat database result, you can use recursion. Here's an example implementation in PHP:

```
function buildNestedArray($flatArray, $parentId = null) {
  $nestedArray = array();
  foreach ($flatArray as $item) {
    if ($item['parent_id'] == $parentId) {
      $children = buildNestedArray($flatArray, $item['id']);
      if (!empty($children)) {
        $item['children'] = $children;
      }
      $nestedArray[] = $item;
    }
  }
  return $nestedArray;
}
```

This function takes in your flat database result, as well as the ID of the parent you want to start building the nested array from (which defaults to `null` for the top-level parent). It uses a `foreach` loop to iterate through each item in the flat array, checking if it has a `parent_id` that matches the current `$parentId`. If it does, it recursively calls itself with `$item['id']` as the new `$parentId` to build the children of that item. If there are children, it adds them to the current item by creating a `children` key and assigning the nested children array to it. Then it adds the current item to the `$nestedArray`, which will eventually be returned as the final output.

Here's an example usage of this function:

```
$flatArray = [
  ['id' => 1, 'name' => 'Home', 'parent_id' => null],
  ['id' => 2, 'name' => 'About', 'parent_id' => null],
  ['id' => 3, 'name' => 'Team', 'parent_id' => 2],
  ['id' => 4, 'name' => 'History', 'parent_id' => 2],
  ['id' => 5, 'name' => 'Contact', 'parent_id' => null],
];

$nestedArray = buildNestedArray($flatArray);
echo json_encode($nestedArray);
```

This will output the following nested array:

