One way to do this is by using the CancellationToken class provided by .NET. 

First, create a CancellationTokenSource object that generates a CancellationToken. This token is passed to the background thread that is responsible for the audio-file-fetching and audio file playback operations. The background thread can check regularly for the token whether it is cancelled or not during the running operation. 

If the user decides to cancel the task, the CancellationTokenSource object's Cancel method should be called. This will cause the CancellationToken property of the CancellationTokenSource object to transition into a cancelled state. 

The background thread should then monitor the token for cancellation state changes. If it detects that the token has been cancelled, it should stop the operation and cleanly terminate any associated resources. 

Here's an example of using CancellationToken in C#:

```csharp
CancellationTokenSource cancellationTokenSource = new CancellationTokenSource();
CancellationToken cancellationToken = cancellationTokenSource.Token;

// Pass the token to the background thread
Task.Run(() =>
{
    while (!cancellationToken.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        // Perform the audio-file-fetching and audio file playback operations
        // regularly check the cancellation token
        // if the token is cancelled, throw CancellationToken exception
    }

    // Clean up resources
}, cancellationToken);

