{
    cancellationTokenSource.Cancel();
    // ...
}
```

This will allow you to gracefully cancel an operation in progress, preventing the loss of resources and avoiding potential problems that may occur when a user cancels an operation.

You can use a technique called "debouncing" to call the resize function only once the user has finished resizing the browser window. Debouncing is a concept where a function call is postponed until after a certain amount of time has elapsed. In your case, you can use the setTimeout and clearTimeout functions to implement debouncing in your resize function.

Here's an example code snippet that demonstrates the use of debouncing in the resize function:

```
$(window).resize(function() {
  clearTimeout(window.resizedFinished);
  window.resizedFinished = setTimeout(function(){
    // your code here
    console.log('resize finished');
  }, 250);
});
```

In this code, we set a timeout of 250 milliseconds to wait for the user to finish resizing the window. If the user resizes the window again within that 250-millisecond window, the clearTimeout function cancels the previous setTimeout function call and starts the timer again. This way, the resize function is only called once the user has finished resizing the window.

