There are a few alternatives for binding methods inside the render method to avoid performance issues:

1. Bind in the constructor: Simply bind the method in the constructor and assign it to the class instance. This way, the method is only bound once, during instance initialization, and can be reused in each render call without creating new methods.

Example:

```
class TodoList extends React.Component {
  constructor(props) {
    super(props);
    this.handleDelete = this.handleDelete.bind(this);
  }

  handleDelete(todoName) {
    // Code to delete todo item from array
  }

  render() {
    return (
      <div>
        {this.props.todos.map((todo, index) => (
          <TodoItem
            key={index}
            todo={todo}
            onClick={() => this.handleDelete(todo.name)}
          />
        ))}
      </div>
    );
  }
}
```

2. Use arrow functions: Arrow functions do not create a new object each time they are called, so they are a good alternative for binding methods inside the render method.

Example:

```
class TodoList extends React.Component {
  handleDelete(todoName) {
    // Code to delete todo item from array
  }

  render() {
    return (
      <div>
        {this.props.todos.map((todo, index) => (
          <TodoItem
            key={index}
            todo={todo}
            onClick={() => this.handleDelete(todo.name)}
          />
        ))}
      </div>
    );
  }
}
```

3. Use bind outside the render method: If you need more control over the binding, you can bind the method outside the render method and assign it to a class property. This way, you can control when the method is bound and how it is called.

Example:

```
class TodoList extends React.Component {
  handleDelete(todoName) {
    // Code to delete todo item from array
  }

  handleClick = (todoName) => {
    this.handleDelete(todoName);
  };

  render() {
    return (
      <div>
        {this.props.todos.map((todo, index) => (
          <TodoItem key={index} todo={todo} onClick={this.handleClick.bind(this, todo.name)} />
        ))}
      </div>
    );
  }
}
```

These alternatives ensure that the same method is reused during re-renders, resulting in better performance. For more information, you can check out the official React documentation on event handling and function binding.

