var dict1 = new Dictionary<string, int>() { { "one", 1 }, { "two", 2 } };
var dict2 = new Dictionary<string, int>() { { "three", 3 }, { "four", 4 } };
var dict3 = new Dictionary<string, int>() { { "five", 5 }, { "six", 6 } };

var mergedDict = dict1.Concat(dict2)
                .Concat(dict3)
                .GroupBy(d => d.Key)
                .ToDictionary(d => d.Key, d => d.First().Value);
```

In this example, we have three dictionaries (`dict1`, `dict2`, `dict3`) that we want to merge into one. `Concat` is used to combine the dictionaries into one sequence, and then `GroupBy` is used to group the elements by their key. Finally, `ToDictionary` is used to create a new dictionary with the grouped data, using the first value of each group.

Regarding duplicate keys, this approach will use the value of the first dictionary encountered that has that key. If there are multiple values for a key in the same dictionary, it doesn't matter which one is used as long as it's consistent.

