Yes, you can make a borderless form movable by handling the `MouseDown`, `MouseMove`, and `MouseUp` events.

Here is some sample code that demonstrates how to achieve this:

```
public partial class Form1 : Form
{
    private bool isDragging = false;
    private Point lastCursorPosition;

    public Form1()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
    }

    private void Form1_MouseDown(object sender, MouseEventArgs e)
    {
        isDragging = true;
        lastCursorPosition = e.Location;
    }

    private void Form1_MouseMove(object sender, MouseEventArgs e)
    {
        if (isDragging)
        {
            Point diff = new Point(
                e.Location.X - lastCursorPosition.X,
                e.Location.Y - lastCursorPosition.Y);
            this.Location = new Point(this.Location.X + diff.X, this.Location.Y + diff.Y);
            lastCursorPosition = e.Location;
        }
    }

    private void Form1_MouseUp(object sender, MouseEventArgs e)
    {
        isDragging = false;
    }
}
```

In this code, we create three event handlers for `MouseDown`, `MouseMove`, and `MouseUp`. When the user clicks on the form, we set a flag (`isDragging`) to indicate that the form is being moved, and we store the current mouse position. As the user moves the mouse, we update the form's location based on the difference between the current mouse position and the last stored position. Finally, when the user releases the mouse, we reset the flag to indicate that the form is no longer being moved.

You can attach these event handlers to your borderless form by adding them to the `MouseDown`, `MouseMove`, and `MouseUp` events in the form's designer or in code.

If you want to take this further, you can also implement drag handles or a title bar to add more visual cues for dragging the form. You can also add keyboard support, such as using the arrow keys to move the form, using the `KeyDown` event. 

