Handling screen orientation changes can be tricky, especially when dealing with background threads and UI elements like progress dialogs. In this case, one approach you can take is to use a retained fragment to manage the background thread and progress dialog. The retained fragment will survive the screen orientation change and can continue to communicate with the activity, even if it is recreated.

Here are the steps to implement this approach:

1. Create a new class that extends `Fragment`. This fragment will hold the background thread and progress dialog.
```
public class MyRetainedFragment extends Fragment {
    private MyBackgroundThread mBackgroundThread;
    private ProgressDialog mProgressDialog;

    // Add any other data or methods you need to manage the thread and dialog
}
```

2. Override the `onCreate()` method and call `setRetainInstance(true)`. This will tell Android to keep the fragment around even if the activity is destroyed and recreated.
```
public void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {
    super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
    setRetainInstance(true);
    // Initialize any data or methods you need
}
```

3. Start the background thread and show the progress dialog in the `onStart()` method of the activity. If the fragment already exists, you can get a reference to it and use it instead of creating a new one.
```
public void onStart() {
    super.onStart();
    MyRetainedFragment fragment = (MyRetainedFragment) getSupportFragmentManager().findFragmentByTag("myFragmentTag");
    if (fragment == null) {
        fragment = new MyRetainedFragment();
        getSupportFragmentManager().beginTransaction().add(fragment, "myFragmentTag").commit();
    }
    if (fragment.getBackgroundThread() == null) {
        fragment.startBackgroundThread();
        fragment.showProgressDialog();
    } else {
        fragment.updateProgressDialog();
    }
}
```

4. Implement methods in the retained fragment to manage the background thread and progress dialog. These methods can communicate with the activity through a listener interface or by calling activity methods directly.
```
public class MyRetainedFragment extends Fragment {
    private MyBackgroundThread mBackgroundThread;
    private ProgressDialog mProgressDialog;
    private MyListener mListener;

    public void startBackgroundThread() {
        mBackgroundThread = new MyBackgroundThread();
        mBackgroundThread.start();
    }

    public void showProgressDialog() {
        mProgressDialog = new ProgressDialog(getActivity());
        mProgressDialog.setMessage("Loading...");
        mProgressDialog.show();
    }

    public void updateProgressDialog() {
        // Update the progress dialog if it is still showing
        if (mProgressDialog != null && mProgressDialog.isShowing()) {
            mProgressDialog.setProgress(mBackgroundThread.getProgress());
        }
    }

    // Add any other data or methods you need

    public interface MyListener {
        void onBackgroundThreadFinished();
    }
}
```

5. When the background thread finishes, call a method on the activity or use the listener interface to notify the activity. This will allow the activity to dismiss the progress dialog and perform any other necessary cleanup.
```
public class MyBackgroundThread extends Thread {
    private int mProgress;

    public void run() {
        // Perform network activity
        mProgress = 100;
        MyRetainedFragment fragment = (MyRetainedFragment) getFragmentManager().findFragmentByTag("myFragmentTag");
        if (fragment != null) {
            fragment.getListener().onBackgroundThreadFinished();
        }
    }

    public int getProgress() {
        return mProgress;
    }
}
```

By using a retained fragment to manage the background thread and progress dialog, you can ensure that your app handles screen orientation changes gracefully. Additionally, this approach can be extended to other types of long-running tasks or to manage other types of UI elements that need to survive configuration changes. If you need more information on retained fragments or background threads, you can check out the official Android documentation: 

- Fragments: https://developer.android.com/guide/fragments/index.html
- Background Processing: https://developer.android.com/guide/background/index.html

