Yes, it is a good practice to properly manage threads in your application to avoid potential issues such as resource exhaustion or performance degradation. However, the use of `Thread.sleep()` alone does not necessarily require you to remove it explicitly as it will automatically exit when it has completed its execution.

If you want to explicitly stop the execution of a thread in your Java application, you can call the `interrupt()` method on your `Thread` object. This method will cause the thread to throw an `InterruptedException` the next time it blocks or waits on a monitor.

Here's an example of how to interrupt a thread:

```java
