The code you are referring to is the jQuery Plugin Boilerplate (https://github.com/jquery-boilerplate/jquery-boilerplate/blob/master/src/jquery.boilerplate.js). It is a template that provides a consistent structure for writing jQuery plugins. Here's what each section of the boilerplate does:

1. Wrapping the code in a self-invoking anonymous function:

(function ($) {
  // Plugin code goes here
})(jQuery);

This is a common JavaScript pattern that creates a closure. It ensures that any variables declared in the plugin code do not pollute the global namespace, and allows us to use the $ shorthand for the jQuery object within the scope of the plugin.

2. Adding the plugin to the jQuery prototype:

$.fn.myPlugin = function () {
  // Plugin code goes here
}

This is how we extend the jQuery object with a new method that can be called on a jQuery collection. For example, if we have a list of elements with class "my-class", we can call our plugin like this: $(".my-class").myPlugin();

3. Defining default plugin options:

var defaults = {
  option1: "default value",
  option2: 123,
  option3: true
};

options = $.extend(defaults, options);

This section defines default options for the plugin. The "options" argument is an object that can be passed in to customize the behavior of the plugin. The $.extend() method merges the passed-in options with the default options.

4. Creating a private method:

function privateMethod() {
  // Code goes here
}

This can be used to encapsulate helper functions or any code that should not be accessible from outside the plugin.

5. Initializing the plugin:

return this.each(function () {
  var $this = $(this);
  // Plugin code goes here
});

Finally, this section initializes the plugin on each element in the jQuery collection. The `each()` method allows us to perform the same action on each element in the collection, and the `$(this)` shorthand allows us to work with the current element within the loop.

Regarding your question about the different ways of writing a plugin:

- Type 1 is the simplest and most straightforward approach. It creates a new function in the global namespace, which can be called from anywhere, even outside of a jQuery context. However, this means that the function will not be chainable like a jQuery plugin.
- Type 2 is similar to Type 1, but it is namespaced with the plugin name to avoid naming conflicts with other global functions. It is still not chainable.
- Type 3 is the most common and recommended approach. It creates a new method on the jQuery prototype, which can be called on a jQuery object and is chainable.

