To achieve the desired effect of zooming in/out the ImageView itself instead of the image within it, you can use the `ScaleAnimation` class in your code. Here's an example implementation:

```
float zoomFactor = 1f;
imageView.setOnTouchListener(new View.OnTouchListener() {
    @Override
    public boolean onTouch(View v, MotionEvent event) {
        switch (event.getAction() & MotionEvent.ACTION_MASK) {
            case MotionEvent.ACTION_POINTER_DOWN:
                zoomFactor = getZoomFactor(event);
                break;
            case MotionEvent.ACTION_MOVE:
                float newZoomFactor = getZoomFactor(event);
                float scale = newZoomFactor / zoomFactor;
                zoomImage(scale, imageView);
                zoomFactor = newZoomFactor;
                break;
        }
        return true;
    }
});

private float getZoomFactor(MotionEvent event) {
    if (event.getPointerCount() < 2) {
        return 1f;
    }
    float x = event.getX(0) - event.getX(1);
    float y = event.getY(0) - event.getY(1);
    return (float) Math.sqrt(x * x + y * y);
}

private void zoomImage(float scale, ImageView view) {
    float width = view.getWidth();
    float height = view.getHeight();
    float newWidth = width * scale;
    float newHeight = height * scale;

    // Limit max and min zoom factor
    if (newWidth < 100 || newWidth > 2000) {
        return;
    }
    if (newHeight < 100 || newHeight > 2000) {
        return;
    }

    ScaleAnimation scaleAnimation = new ScaleAnimation(
        1f, scale, 1f, scale,
        width/2, height/2);
    scaleAnimation.setDuration(0);
    scaleAnimation.setFillAfter(true);
    view.startAnimation(scaleAnimation);
    ViewGroup.LayoutParams layoutParams = view.getLayoutParams();
    layoutParams.width = (int) newWidth;
    layoutParams.height = (int) newHeight;
    view.setLayoutParams(layoutParams);
}
```

In the `onTouch()` method, the `getZoomFactor()` method calculates the distance between two fingers on the screen to determine the current zoom factor. The `zoomImage()` method takes the scale factor and the ImageView and applies the scaling to the image view by animating the scale changes and updating the layout params accordingly. The width and height of the ImageView will be increased and decreased while zooming in and out. 

Note that this is just one way to achieve zooming in and out of an ImageView, there are many other approaches with their own benefits and drawbacks. If you're interested in learning more, see some additional resources:

- [Adding Pinch-to-Zoom Gesture to an ImageView in Android](https://medium.com/@mohitgupta_20036/adding-pinch-to-zoom-gesture-to-an-imageview-in-android-ab6e9c451299)
- [Zooming and Panning with GestureDetector and View.OnTouchListener - Android Developers Blog](https://android-developers.googleblog.com/2010/06/making-sense-of-multitouch.html)
