In React, components render when their props or state changes. Simply subscribing to an external observable and hoping that the component re-renders is not an effective way to update a component. One way to force a component to update and re-render is by using its state. 

You can create state within the component and then update that state whenever the external observable that you're listening to changes. This will cause the component to re-render and display updated information. Here's an example: 

```
import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

function MyComponent() {
  const [myData, setMyData] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    // subscribe to your external observable, and update 'myData' whenever it changes
    return () => {
      // unsubscribe from the observable when the component unmounts
    };
  }, []);

  return (
    <div>
      {myData ? <div>{myData}</div> : <div>Loading...</div>}
      <button onClick={() => setMyData('new data')}>
        Update My Data
      </button>
    </div>
  );
}

export default MyComponent;
```

In the example above, we create some state with `useState` to hold `myData`, which could be the value of your external observable. We then use `useEffect` to subscribe to the observable and update `myData` whenever it changes. 

Finally, we render `myData` in the component, and provide a button that can be clicked to update that same state. This will cause the component to re-render and display the updated data.

If you don't want to use state in your component, you can look into using `forceUpdate`. However, keep in mind that using `forceUpdate` can cause performance issues and should be used with caution.

