When your program receives a kill signal, it's important to handle any necessary clean-up procedures gracefully. This can be especially important in cases where your program may be doing things like managing resources or maintaining state that could be corrupted or lost if those resources are not released properly.

The signal handling mechanism can be used to register a cleanup function that can be called when a SIGINT signal is received for example. In C programming, you can use the `signal` function to register a function that will be called when the signal is received. Here's an example:

```c
#include <signal.h>
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

void cleanup() {
  printf("Performing cleanup...\n");
  // Release resources and perform any necessary cleanup here
  exit(0); // Exit cleanly
}

void handle_signal(int signal) {
  printf("Received signal %d\n", signal);
  cleanup();
}

int main() {
  // Register our signal handler
  signal(SIGINT, handle_signal);

  // Run our program logic here
  while(1) {
    // Do something useful
  }

  return 0;
}
```

The `cleanup` function is defined to perform any necessary cleanup operations when the program is interrupted. Once the cleanup has completed, the program exits gracefully using `exit(0)`.

Note that if you're using the `kill` shell command with the `-9` option, you may not be able to capture the signal and perform any cleanup. In this case, it's better to use a different signal (e.g. SIGTERM) or use the `kill` command without the `-9` option to allow for proper cleanup.

